As Nigeria marks Democracy Day, today, President Muhammadu Buhari has been urged to without further delay establish the National Commission for Persons with Disabilities so that this category of Nigerians would begin to enjoy the dividends of democracy which have eluded them since 1999 when the country embraced the democratic system of governance. The call was contained in a statement issued by the chairman and chief executive officer (CEO) of a not-for-profit organisation, DisabledWorld Nigeria Advocacy (DWNA), Mr Paul Uwadima in Abuja yesterday ahead of the Democracy Day celebration. Uwadima said that The Discrimination Against Persons With Disabilities (Prohibition) Act, 2018 that had been signed into law by President Muhammadu Buhari for over a year establishes the National Commission for Persons with Disabilities as a corporate body with common seal and perpetual succession. He noted that the National Commission for Persons with Disabilities is established in Section 31 of the Act with Executive Secretary as the head. He said, “ According to the Act the commission’s responsibilities include policy formulation and implementation, public enlightenment, data collection and record-keeping of information regarding persons with disabilities, receipt of complaints from persons with disabilities whose rights have been violated and institution of schemes which promote the welfare of persons with disabilities.” He noted that without the constitution of the commission it would be difficult to access the impact of the law in improving the welfare of the physically challenged and ensuring that the rights of persons with disabilities are not violated. While commending President Muhammadu Buhari for assenting to the Act, which previous Presidents, Olusegun Obasanjo and Goodluck Jonathan, respectively, failed to do, he said that the major task facing the President and indeed the whole country is to facilitate the implementation of the law. The CEO of DWNA, who is also an author and media practitioner, noted that the Act further provides that discrimination is prohibited in public transportation facilities and service providers are to make provision for the physically, visually and hearing impaired and all persons howsoever challenged, adding that this also applies to seaports, railways and airport facilities. The rights and privileges include education, healthcare, priority in accommodation and emergencies.